"Warnock D.D., Lehmann J., Kuyper T.W., Rillig M.C.","Mycorrhizal responses to biochar in soil - Concepts and mechanisms",2007,"Plant and Soil","300","1-2",,"9","20",,,10.1007/s11104-007-9391-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-35748976260&partnerID=40&md5=ea7aa12757676951f44ecfca049b0de5","Microbial Ecology Program, Division of Biological Sciences, University of Montana, Missoula, MT 59812, United States; Department of Crop and Soil Sciences, Cornell University, Ithaca, NY 14853, United States; Department of Soil Quality, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 47, 6700 AA Wageningen, Netherlands; Institut für Biologie, Freie Universität Berlin, Altensteinstr. 6, 14195 Berlin, Germany","Warnock, D.D., Microbial Ecology Program, Division of Biological Sciences, University of Montana, Missoula, MT 59812, United States; Lehmann, J., Department of Crop and Soil Sciences, Cornell University, Ithaca, NY 14853, United States; Kuyper, T.W., Department of Soil Quality, Wageningen University, P.O. Box 47, 6700 AA Wageningen, Netherlands; Rillig, M.C., Microbial Ecology Program, Division of Biological Sciences, University of Montana, Missoula, MT 59812, United States, Institut für Biologie, Freie Universität Berlin, Altensteinstr. 6, 14195 Berlin, Germany","Experiments suggest that biomass-derived black carbon (biochar) affects microbial populations and soil biogeochemistry. Both biochar and mycorrhizal associations, ubiquitous symbioses in terrestrial ecosystems, are potentially important in various ecosystem services provided by soils, contributing to sustainable plant production, ecosystem restoration, and soil carbon sequestration and hence mitigation of global climate change. As both biochar and mycorrhizal associations are subject to management, understanding and exploiting interactions between them could be advantageous. Here we focus on biochar effects on mycorrhizal associations. After reviewing the experimental evidence for such effects, we critically examine hypotheses pertaining to four mechanisms by which biochar could influence mycorrhizal abundance and/or functioning. These mechanisms are (in decreasing order of currently available evidence supporting them): (a) alteration of soil physico-chemical properties; (b) indirect effects on mycorrhizae through effects on other soil microbes; (c) plant-fungus signaling interference and detoxification of allelochemicals on biochar; and (d) provision of refugia from fungal grazers. We provide a roadmap for research aimed at testing these mechanistic hypotheses. © 2007 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.","Arbuscular mycorrhiza; Biochar; Carbon storage; Ectomycorrhiza; Restoration; Terra preta","allelochemical; arbuscular mycorrhiza; biogeochemistry; biomass; black carbon; carbon sequestration; charcoal; climate change; detoxification; ectomycorrhiza; experimental study; fungus; mitigation; restoration ecology; soil microorganism; soil property; terrestrial ecosystem; Arbuscular; Fungi",,,,,,"Akiyama, K., Matsuzaki, K.-I., Hayashi, H., Plant sesquiterpenes induce hyphal branching in arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi (2005) Nature, 435, pp. 824-827; Angelini, J., Castro, S., Fabra, A., Alterations in root colonization and nodC gene induction in the peanut-rhizobia interaction under acidic conditions (2003) Plant Physiol Biochem, 41, pp. 289-294; Antal Jr., M.J., Grønli, M., The art, science, and technology of charcoal production (2003) Indust Engin Chem Res, 42, pp. 1619-1640; Aspray, T.J., Eirian Jones, E., Whipps, J.M., Bending, G.D., Importance of mycorrhization helper bacteria cell density and metabolite localization for the Pinus sylvestris-Lactarius rufus symbiosis (2006) FEMS Microbiol Ecol, 56, pp. 25-33; Bais, H.P., Park, S.W., Weir, T.L., Callaway, R.M., Vivanco, J.M., How plants communicate using the underground information superhighway (2004) Trends Plant Sci, 9, pp. 26-32; Bais, H.P., Weir, T.L., Perry, L.G., Gilroy, S., Vivanco, J.M., The role of root exudates in r